Company stats \n\n Winners & losers \n\n 52-week highs/lows \n\n Top by value/volume \n\n Top 40 Companies \n\n JSE sectors \n\n Business calendar \n\n Director dealings \n\n Dividend watch \n\n Dividend History \n\n Company contacts \n\n Annual Reports \n\n Heatmap \n\n \n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n JSE Indices \n Value \n Move \n % \n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n \n \n \n World Indices \n Value \n 1 day \n 7 day \n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n Currencies \n Value \n Move \n % \n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n \n \n \n Commodities \n Value \n Move \n % \n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n \n\n SHARES\n\n \n\n \n Facebook\n \n Twitter\n \n LinkedIn\n \n WhatsApp\n \n Email\n \n Print\n \n \n \n 2 VOTES\n \n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Next article:\n \n The unfair burden of someone else’s financial choices \n \n \n \n &times;\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n Share this article \n &times; \n \n\n \n \n \n Shares \n \n\n \n Facebook\n \n\n \n Twitter\n \n\n \n LinkedIn\n \n\n \n WhatsApp\n \n\n \n \n Email\n \n\n \n \n Print\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n Use your own intelligence to make smart investment decisions \n\n \n \n \n \n\n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n Join our free mailing list for top business news.\n \n\n \n &times;\n \n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n \n\n \n \n \n\n \n \n \n\n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n \n Financial Advisor''s view \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Use your own intelligence to make smart investment decisions \n \n \n Don’t mistake today’s AI boom for something completely new: Why you should be cautious and avoid overpaying for tech that could look different a few years from now. \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Schalk Louw - PSG Wealth Old Oak \n \n · \n \n \n 27 May 2026, 04:00 \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n The long-term potential of AI is undeniable, however, avoid assuming that today''s shortages, elevated prices and share prices will remain that way forever. Image: AdobeStock \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n My children were born in the early stages of the dot-com era, and the prevailing educational advice at the time was that children should be exposed to a computer as early as possible, simply because it was “going to take over the entire world”.\n\n My wife and I walked into a computer store and the technician talked us into buying a Pentium 4 computer, which set us back a whopping R15 000 – our entire savings, and possibly a little more. \n \n ADVERTISEMENT\n\n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n CONTINUE READING BELOW\n\n Given the enormous demand, he spoke about the massive shortages but said this ‘advanced’ computer would last for years, or even a decade. Everybody in our professional circles, social circles, and even the media sounded exactly like the technician: You had to get in and get in now or lose out.\n\n Well, five years later I couldn’t even use the computer as a doorstop. It had already become obsolete. Fast-forward 25 years to today, 2026. Among all its other functions, you can now find the latest technology in smartphones and so many other appliances and gadgets.\n\n Read: A history of market bubbles \n\n A smartphone, for example, with 8GB of RAM, 256GB of storage and countless other features that people with PCs in the 2000s could only dream of now costs about R7 500. It has more than 15 times the memory and six times the storage of a PC in the 2000s, which I paid R15 000 for, and fits in the palm of your hand. And here is the most important point: no shortages.\n\n What am I getting at? Be very careful not to do what my wife and I, along with millions of other people did in the early 2000s: to think, firstly, that AI and rapid technology advancements are something we have never experienced before – because we have.\n\n And more importantly, be cautious about getting caught up in the frenzy and investing in items that could have been bought for considerably less, with considerably better technology in a few years time.\n\n This applies not only to all thing’s semiconductor-related, but equally to the prices currently being paid for the shares of these companies.\n\n Read: AI: The next big thing or just hot air? \n\n \n\n Graph 1 Philadelphia Semiconductor Index (source LSEG) \n\n Take, for example, two of the well-known PC manufacturers of the 2000s: IBM and Dell. During the build-up of the dot-com internet frenzy between 1996 and 2000, and driven by the massive shortage of computers, these two companies grew by 400% and 3 600% respectively over a roughly four-year period. \n \n ADVERTISEMENT:\n\n \n \n \n \n \n\n \n\n CONTINUE READING BELOW\n\n Nobody could convince you, myself included, that computers and the internet were not going to take over the world, and that if you wanted the internet, you were simply going to have to pay up for the computers and the parts.\n\n \n\n Graph 2 IBM and Dell share prices between 1996 and 2006 (source LSEG) \n\n Without giving away the ending for anyone who may one day still want to read the ‘book’, less than two years later, the shortages disappeared, technology improved, and these companies lost 60% and 250% of their respective values and went virtually nowhere for nearly a decade.\n\n Read: Stories from the 90s: Lessons from the dot-com era \n\n I want to conclude by saying that I am in no way underestimating or trivialising the scale and significance of AI. This is most certainly going to keep growing. However, do not make the mistake of thinking that the current shortages and elevated prices, both in the components and in the share prices of the companies that manufacture them, are going to remain that way forever.\n\n Both technology and manufacturing will, just as they did in the 2000s, catch up and self-correct.\n\n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Was this article by Schalk helpful?\n\n \n \n 2 \n \n \n \n\n \n \n \n \n \n 